      "\n          intro n\n          by_contra h₈\n          have h₉ : a n > La := by linarith\n          -- If `a n > La`, then since `a` is monotone, all subsequent terms are also greater than `La`, which contradicts the convergence to `La`\n          have h₁₀ : ∀ k ≥ n, a k ≥ a n := by\n            intro k hk\n            exact h₄ (by linarith)\n          have h₁₁ : ∀ k ≥ n, a k > La := by\n            intro k hk\n            linarith [h₁₀ k hk]\n          have h₁₂ : Filter.Tendsto a Filter.atTop (nhds La) := by\n            rw [Metric.tendsto_nhds] at *\n            simp_all [SeqLim]\n          have h₁₃ : ∃ (N : ℕ), ∀ (k : ℕ), k ≥ N → |a k - La| < a n - La := by\n            have h₁₄ : Filter.Tendsto a Filter.atTop (nhds La) := h₁₂\n            have h₁₅ : Metric.tendsto_atTop (a : ℕ → ℝ) (La : ℝ) := by\n              simp_all [Metric.tendsto_nhds]\n            have h₁₆ : ∀ ε > 0, ∃ (N : ℕ), ∀ (k : ℕ), k ≥ N → |a k - La| < ε := by\n              intro ε ε_pos\n              have h₁₇ := Metric.tendsto_atTop.mp h₁₅ ε ε_pos\n              obtain ⟨N, hN⟩ := h₁₇\n              refine' ⟨N, _⟩\n              intro k hk\n              exact hN k hk\n            have h₁₈ := h₁₆ (a n - La) (by linarith)\n            obtain ⟨N, hN⟩ := h₁₈\n            refine' ⟨N, _⟩\n            intro k hk\n            exact hN k hk\n          obtain ⟨N, hN⟩ := h₁₃\n          have h₁₉ := hN (max n N) (le_max_right _ _)\n          have h₂₀ : a (max n N) > La := h₁₁ (max n N) (le_max_left _ _)\n          have h₂₁ : |a (max n N) - La| < a n - La := h₁₉\n          have h₂₂ : a (max n N) - La > 0 := by linarith\n          have h₂₃ : |a (max n N) - La| = a (max n N) - La := by\n            rw [abs_of_nonneg (by linarith)]\n          rw [h₂₃] at h₂₁\n          linarith\n        exact h₇ n\n      exact h₃\n    exact h₁\n  exact h",
      "\n  intro n\n  have h₁ : a n ≤ not_top (Set.univ : Set ℝ) := by\n    apply le_not_top\n  -- Since `a` is monotone and bounded above by `b 0`, it converges to `La`, and all terms are bounded by `La`.\n  have h₂ : a n ≤ La := by\n    -- Use the fact that the sequence `a_n` is increasing and bounded above to deduce that each term is less than or equal to their limit.\n    have h₃ : a n ≤ a (n + 1) := aMono (by linarith)\n    have h₄ : a n ≤ a (n + 2) := by\n      calc\n        a n ≤ a (n + 1) := aMono (by linarith)\n        _ ≤ a (n + 2) := aMono (by linarith)\n    have h₅ : a n ≤ a 0 := by\n      -- Since `a` is increasing, we have `a n ≤ a 0` for all `n`. This step would only work if `a` were decreasing, which it is not.\n      -- This approach is incorrect because we assumed the wrong direction for the monotonicity of `a`.\n      -- Correct approach: If the sequence `a` is increasing, then it would be that for all `n`, `a n ≥ a 0`, which is not useful for proving `a n ≤ La`.\n      -- Correction: Actually, in Lean, `Monotone` means that if `n ≤ m`, then `a n ≤ a m`, i.e., the sequence is non-decreasing. Therefore, `a n ≤ a m` for `n ≤ m`. However, in our case, we need to prove that `a n ≤ La` for any `n`. The limit `La` is the supremum of the sequence, since it's increasing and bounded above (`a n ≤ b 0`).\n      -- This is actually more complicated than we thought. Instead of trying to use the property of `a` being increasing, it might be easier to use the fact that `a` converges to `La`, which means that for any `n`, `a n ≤ La + ε` for sufficiently small `ε`. But this requires working with the definition of limits, which is not straightforward because Lean's `SeqLim` uses `Filter.Tendsto`.\n      -- Correction: The correct approach is to realize that since `a` is increasing and bounded above (by `b 0`), its limit `La` is the supremum of the sequence. Therefore, for any `n`, `a n ≤ sup a n = La`. \n      -- To avoid complicated proofs, we can use that the se